entry.sn:
To be complacent toward; to give way to; not to oppose or restrain; 
   when said of a habit, desire, etc.:
   to give free course to; to give one's self up to; as, to indulge sloth, pride, selfishness, or inclinations;


   when said of a person:
   to yield to the desire of; to gratify by compliance; to humor; to withhold restraint from; as, to indulge children in their caprices or willfulness; to indulge one's self with a rest or in pleasure.

   Hope in another life implies that we indulge ourselves in the gratifications of this very sparingly.

entry.note:
☞ The typical Insecta, or hexapod insects, are divided into several orders, viz.: 
            Hymenoptera
         , as the bees and ants; 
            Diptera
         , as the common flies, gnats, and mosquitos; 
            Aphaniptera
         , or fleas; 
            Lepidoptera
         , or moths and butterflies; 
            Neuroptera
         , as the ant-lions and hellgamite; 
            Coleoptera
         , or beetles; 
            Hemiptera
         , as bugs, lice, aphids; 
            Orthoptera
         , as grasshoppers and cockroaches; 
            Pseudoneuroptera
         , as the dragon flies and termites; 
            Euplexoptera
         , or earwigs; 
            Thysanura
         , as the springtails, podura, and lepisma. See these words in the Vocabulary.
